00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:43.790
of the plant.

00:37:43.790 --> 00:37:45.749
And then there's a second
life, about 15 years.

00:37:45.749 --> 00:37:47.664
I don't have to go into
the economic structure

00:37:47.664 --> 00:37:48.790
unless you want me to.

00:37:48.790 --> 00:37:51.760
And in California now,
the cost structure

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:54.251
is such that it's going to
be much harder to recoup.

00:37:54.251 --> 00:37:55.750
Because it's gone
from $400 million,

00:37:55.750 --> 00:37:59.790
which is, in Israel, for
building a comparable plant,

00:37:59.790 --> 00:38:03.120
to one now in the US,
that plant costing

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:04.580
about a billion dollars.

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:06.387
So it's a higher cost.

00:38:06.387 --> 00:38:07.220
That's first of all.

00:38:07.220 --> 00:38:11.170
Second of all is you
have it exactly right.

00:38:11.170 --> 00:38:14.010
Politicians do not
like spending money

00:38:14.010 --> 00:38:16.530
on invisible infrastructure.

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:19.220
So your question sort of have
had a implication of that.

00:38:19.220 --> 00:38:23.330
So politicians, mayors,
governors, city councilmen

00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:26.779
and women, they focus very
much on the incentives

00:38:26.779 --> 00:38:27.570
that they're given.

00:38:27.570 --> 00:38:29.190
And Boris and I,
before we came here,

00:38:29.190 --> 00:38:33.120
were talking about why we need a
different governance structure,

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:35.040
because we are in a
different world now.

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.510
And we are in a different
world in water as well.

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:40.990
So mayors are in office
four years, or eight years,

00:38:40.990 --> 00:38:41.870
or maybe 12 years.

00:38:41.870 --> 00:38:44.590
And I told you earlier, it takes
10 to 20 years to build out

00:38:44.590 --> 00:38:46.300
a water infrastructure system.

00:38:46.300 --> 00:38:49.335
So a mayor has
almost no incentive,

00:38:49.335 --> 00:38:51.490
from an electoral
point of view, to be

00:38:51.490 --> 00:38:54.620
focusing on what is an expensive
infrastructure, to build it

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:55.630
out.

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:59.440
He has lots of incentive to
build parks, and schools,

00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:03.210
and hospitals, or to cut taxes.

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:05.865
And so therefore,
that's what they do.

00:39:05.865 --> 00:39:08.545
And until citizens
demand that there

00:39:08.545 --> 00:39:12.600
be more water smarts
and more water activity,

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:13.890
it's not going to come.

00:39:13.890 --> 00:39:16.450
And finally, in terms of your
question about agriculture,

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:18.460
it would be a bad
idea-- and I didn't

00:39:18.460 --> 00:39:19.960
make this clear in
my remarks, and I

00:39:19.960 --> 00:39:22.520
should have-- it
would be a bad idea

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:24.570
to be thinking of
desalinating water

00:39:24.570 --> 00:39:26.820
for the purpose
of growing crops.

00:39:26.820 --> 00:39:28.490
Because there are
still water-rich parts

00:39:28.490 --> 00:39:33.090
in the world where it's easier
to grow crops with local water,

00:39:33.090 --> 00:39:35.500
natural water, than
using manufactured water.

00:39:35.500 --> 00:39:38.140
Manufactured water, as
inexpensive as it has become,

00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:41.420
relatively, is
still-- it's a cost.

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:44.130
And therefore, you want
to, if at all possible,

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:48.160
not use desalinated
water for agriculture,

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:49.810
just because of
the cost structure.

00:39:49.810 --> 00:39:52.700
Ideally, you use your
desalinated water

00:39:52.700 --> 00:39:55.210
as a way of topping
off your system,

00:39:55.210 --> 00:39:57.854
and not as a way of
being your system.

00:39:57.854 --> 00:40:00.020
Now, we may reach a point,
because of climate change

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:02.650
and the other macro conditions,
where we have no choice.

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:04.750
Just as we agreed to
spend $4 and $5 a gallon

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:06.522
for our gas for
our cars, we make

00:40:06.522 --> 00:40:07.980
a decision there's
no other choice,

00:40:07.980 --> 00:40:09.800
there may come to that as well.

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:11.646
But I would argue
that the sooner we

00:40:11.646 --> 00:40:13.520
get started on thinking
these things through,

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:15.228
the sooner we get
started on building out

00:40:15.228 --> 00:40:16.910
our infrastructure,
the sooner we

00:40:16.910 --> 00:40:19.520
get started on thinking about
governance and planning,

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:21.550
the smarter that will be.

00:40:21.550 --> 00:40:23.050
We do know something.

00:40:23.050 --> 00:40:25.635
We do know that there's
going to be another drought.

00:40:25.635 --> 00:40:28.010
And then what happens is you
have a couple of rainy days,

00:40:28.010 --> 00:40:31.509
you have a rainy season,
and elected officials

00:40:31.509 --> 00:40:33.050
who don't want to
spend money, or who

00:40:33.050 --> 00:40:35.170
don't want to have
new infrastructure,

00:40:35.170 --> 00:40:37.450
or who don't think that we
should build a desalination

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:39.570
plant because it burns
too much carbon fuel,

00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:41.990
or because it adds
salty water back

00:40:41.990 --> 00:40:45.710
into the ocean-- I have answers
to that as well, within limits.

00:40:45.710 --> 00:40:48.070
It's not that big a problem.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:50.330
They use that as an excuse
to say well, the, aquifers

00:40:50.330 --> 00:40:51.996
are refilling, so why
should we do this?

00:40:51.996 --> 00:40:56.990
And I think that's an abdication
of very important and necessary

00:40:56.990 --> 00:40:57.730
leadership.

00:40:57.730 --> 00:41:00.000
AUDIENCE: Could you
comment on the fact

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:05.220
that this, for Israel,
like, it may have been

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:08.290
a strategic way of thinking.

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:11.830
Because obviously, like,
the geography as such

00:41:11.830 --> 00:41:14.020
is one that forces
you to-- if you

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:16.540
want to have a viable
economy on this land,

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:19.170
you need to think
about the water issue.

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:21.420
Is that something
that helped sort

00:41:21.420 --> 00:41:27.870
of bridge the sort
of bipartisanship

00:41:27.870 --> 00:41:31.790
that you might see
in, let's say, the US,

00:41:31.790 --> 00:41:36.630
where one group of politicians
may be supporting the people,

00:41:36.630 --> 00:41:41.800
and who are holding the water
rights, whereas the other may

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:45.810
be more progressive in trying
to think about these things.

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:51.880
So I guess my question
is how is the support

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:56.640
on both sides of the
political spectrum in Israel

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:57.765
for these kind of projects?

00:41:57.765 --> 00:41:59.940
And where does it come from?

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:03.430
And what would be the lessons
for some of the other parts

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:04.552
of the world?

00:42:04.552 --> 00:42:05.510
SETH SIEGEL: Thank you.

00:42:05.510 --> 00:42:06.670
It's an important question.

00:42:06.670 --> 00:42:08.990
And it gives me the
opportunity to actually speak

00:42:08.990 --> 00:42:11.747
of one of the several ways that
our governance is broken here

00:42:11.747 --> 00:42:13.320
in the United States.

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:15.820
Governance is not just the
elected officials that we have.

00:42:15.820 --> 00:42:20.930
Governance is also the way we
choose to conduct and control

00:42:20.930 --> 00:42:22.630
how we manage our water.

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:24.450
So we have hundreds
and thousands

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:27.880
of different stakeholders
in water here.

00:42:27.880 --> 00:42:30.050
And yet in Israel, what
they made the decision to do

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:35.820
was to build out a system,
and to give one single entity

00:42:35.820 --> 00:42:36.725
enormous control.

00:42:36.725 --> 00:42:40.410
It's a technocratic,
apolitical body,

00:42:40.410 --> 00:42:41.660
and they make the decisions.

00:42:41.660 --> 00:42:43.070
And here's the remarkable thing.

00:42:43.070 --> 00:42:46.620
I interviewed 220
people for the book.

00:42:46.620 --> 00:42:48.470
About-- we didn't
get into it at all.

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:49.947
I didn't talk much
about the effect

00:42:49.947 --> 00:42:51.780
that Israel gives water
to the Palestinians.

00:42:51.780 --> 00:42:53.260
I wanted to understand
the Palestinian water

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:55.400
claims and the Israeli
issues back and forth.

00:42:55.400 --> 00:42:58.260
So I spent a fair amount of
time meeting with Palestinians,

00:42:58.260 --> 00:43:00.540
and NGO heads, and such
to understand that issue.

00:43:00.540 --> 00:43:02.206
And I'm glad to talk
about it, if anyone

00:43:02.206 --> 00:43:04.650
has a question about it.

00:43:04.650 --> 00:43:06.570
But what was
interesting was in the,

00:43:06.570 --> 00:43:10.100
call it maybe 190
other people that I

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:13.710
spoke to, Israeli people,
business executives, government

00:43:13.710 --> 00:43:18.145
officials, stakeholders
in different parts

00:43:18.145 --> 00:43:21.550
of the water equation in
Israel, what I was amazed by

00:43:21.550 --> 00:43:24.830
was the fact that not
a single one of them

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:27.655
suggested that even though
Israel now has privatized

00:43:27.655 --> 00:43:33.740
its economy completely, and even
though Israel now has-- there's

00:43:33.740 --> 00:43:36.000
no state-owned bank, there's
no state-owned airline,

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:38.084
there's no state-owned
telecommunications company.

00:43:38.084 --> 00:43:40.624
All those have been privatized
in the Margaret Thatcher-style

00:43:40.624 --> 00:43:41.240
privatization.

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:44.870
What shocked me was that
not one person I spoke to,

00:43:44.870 --> 00:43:48.000
even when I pushed them, not
professors, not economics

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.050
professors, not
bankers, no one I

00:43:50.050 --> 00:43:53.210
spoke to in the water
equation told me

00:43:53.210 --> 00:43:55.190
that they thought it
would be a good idea

00:43:55.190 --> 00:43:58.675
to make the free market a larger
part of the water equation.

00:43:58.675 --> 00:44:01.300
And so what we have in the
US is that-- I mean, just

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:03.690
to give one example
of California--

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:06.680
if you are along a
river, let's say you're

00:44:06.680 --> 00:44:08.780
along the Colorado River, OK?

00:44:08.780 --> 00:44:12.105
And you have bad soil,
mostly sandy soil,

00:44:12.105 --> 00:44:13.870
and you decide you
want to grow cotton.

00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:15.953
Which again, no reason any
of us should know this,

00:44:15.953 --> 00:44:18.320
but it's a highly
water-consumptive crop.

00:44:18.320 --> 00:44:20.130
And you decide you
want to grow cotton.

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:21.880
And you're right along
the Colorado River.

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:24.400
You can, under
current structure,

00:44:24.400 --> 00:44:27.300
take all the water you
want out of the river.

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:29.020
There's no limits whatsoever.

00:44:29.020 --> 00:44:32.070
You can flood irrigate your
field to your heart's content.

00:44:32.070 --> 00:44:33.550
Now you can't,
then, take the water

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:34.865
and sell it to somebody else.

00:44:34.865 --> 00:44:36.520
It's public property
in that regard,

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:38.640
or it's in the flow of property.

00:44:38.640 --> 00:44:40.380
But for where you
are along the river,

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:42.910
you take all you want,
as much as you want,

00:44:42.910 --> 00:44:45.890
as often as you want.

00:44:45.890 --> 00:44:47.384
That would never fly in Israel.

00:44:47.384 --> 00:44:49.050
What they made the
decision is that they

00:44:49.050 --> 00:44:51.650
need to think about what's
in the best interest,

00:44:51.650 --> 00:44:55.000
the highest best use of
a society altogether.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.500
Now I want to just take issue
with one part of your question

00:44:57.500 --> 00:44:59.320
now.

00:44:59.320 --> 00:45:01.970
And that is the
question about Israel

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:04.090
had necessity in all this.

00:45:04.090 --> 00:45:06.910
And I think that was
not necessarily true.

00:45:06.910 --> 00:45:08.860
Israel could have
made the decision,

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:13.400
as Singapore did, that it would
have no agriculture at all.

00:45:13.400 --> 00:45:15.025
It could have made
the decision that it

00:45:15.025 --> 00:45:19.820
would import 100% of its food,
of its fruits and vegetables,

00:45:19.820 --> 00:45:21.535
from Europe, or from wherever.

00:45:21.535 --> 00:45:22.910
It could have made
that decision.

00:45:22.910 --> 00:45:24.743
Now, there's some
national security reasons.

00:45:24.743 --> 00:45:26.322
Israel is famously isolated.

00:45:26.322 --> 00:45:27.780
And unfortunately,
because of time,

00:45:27.780 --> 00:45:30.280
I didn't have a chance to talk
about what I call in the book

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:33.090
hydro-diplomacy, and the ways
in which Israel opened the door

00:45:33.090 --> 00:45:35.930
to diplomatic relations
with China and India

00:45:35.930 --> 00:45:37.990
through water technology.

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:41.990
Israel understood China and
India's severe water problems,

00:45:41.990 --> 00:45:44.720
and used water as a
door-opener, which now they

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:46.220
have robust and
wonderful relations,

00:45:46.220 --> 00:45:49.620
but used it as a door-opener
to have relations those two.

00:45:49.620 --> 00:45:51.360
But Israel could have
made other choices.

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:53.380
Israel made a decision
to be a country

00:45:53.380 --> 00:45:56.030
like all other countries,
to have a great agriculture

00:45:56.030 --> 00:45:58.860
sector, to feed
their own people,

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:00.402
not too feed their
cattle-- they feed

00:46:00.402 --> 00:46:02.193
their cattle and their
chickens with fodder

00:46:02.193 --> 00:46:03.320
that's grown elsewhere.

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:05.680
But all the fruits and
vegetables they eat

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:07.910
are mostly homegrown.

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:09.490
And they made that decision.

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:11.740
And so therefore, they
had to adapt their economy

00:46:11.740 --> 00:46:13.690
and their water
plans accordingly.

00:46:13.690 --> 00:46:15.990
Now, just imagine if in
the US, first of all,

00:46:15.990 --> 00:46:18.950
imagine that we had a water
system, a water governance

00:46:18.950 --> 00:46:21.570
system, that wasn't
tied to a time that's

00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:26.550
closer to the 19th century, when
there was few people out West,

00:46:26.550 --> 00:46:29.410
when there was abundant
water, when no matter how much

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:31.280
water that farmer
upstream would take,

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:33.450
there was still plenty
more for people downstream.

00:46:33.450 --> 00:46:35.990
But I didn't finish the story.

00:46:35.990 --> 00:46:37.360
What's the problem?

00:46:37.360 --> 00:46:40.720
The problem is by the time
that water gets far west,

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:42.260
by the time it gets
to Los Angeles,

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:46.750
by the time it gets even
to Nevada, it's a trickle.

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:49.764
So you have Lake Mead
now at historic low.

00:46:49.764 --> 00:46:51.680
You ever seen those
pictures of the Hoover Dam

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:52.660
with those water lines?

00:46:52.660 --> 00:46:56.740
If not, if I may say, go
to Google and do a search.

00:46:56.740 --> 00:46:58.840
It's really quite remarkable.

00:46:58.840 --> 00:47:00.570
And so you find
yourself in a situation

00:47:00.570 --> 00:47:03.820
where we have ever less
water, urgently needed,

00:47:03.820 --> 00:47:05.320
because we have a
governance system.

00:47:05.320 --> 00:47:07.240
Now, I don't think it's a
problem of one political party

00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:07.882
or the other.

00:47:07.882 --> 00:47:09.340
I think one political
party is more

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:12.332
given to the free market
than the other, I think.

00:47:12.332 --> 00:47:15.340
But I think it's frankly that
nobody is paying attention

00:47:15.340 --> 00:47:16.630
whatsoever.

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:19.620
It's just off the radar
screen, and that's a problem.

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:23.280
AUDIENCE: So as Boris
mentioned, there

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:25.680
is perhaps, in the
case of Israel,

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:29.530
sort of like a nation-state
interest in developing

00:47:29.530 --> 00:47:30.310
this desert.

00:47:33.160 --> 00:47:36.800
In the case of making
the analogy to the US,

00:47:36.800 --> 00:47:41.570
where its market-driven
forces that really decide what

00:47:41.570 --> 00:47:44.320
happens, what is
the alternative?

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:47.640
Where do you see
the future going?

00:47:47.640 --> 00:47:51.280
What are going to
be the incentives?

00:47:51.280 --> 00:47:54.880
We can't just bury our head
in the sand and say, you know,

00:47:54.880 --> 00:47:56.450
it's not a problem.

00:47:56.450 --> 00:47:58.720
It will bite us at some point.

00:47:58.720 --> 00:48:01.760
SETH SIEGEL: Yeah,
you know, I think--

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:05.140
look, I'm a great believer in,
as I think everyone here is,

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:07.190
in democracies.

00:48:07.190 --> 00:48:12.410
So the problem that democracies
are that crucial decisions get

00:48:12.410 --> 00:48:15.620
pushed off for a very long
time, until they become crises.

00:48:15.620 --> 00:48:20.280
So the premise of your question
implies a smart governance

00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:22.910
system where we
move more rapidly.

00:48:22.910 --> 00:48:24.760
And I'm not as
optimistic as you are.

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:27.800
I see, again and
again in our history,

00:48:27.800 --> 00:48:31.680
where we do ultimately address
problems and address them well,

00:48:31.680 --> 00:48:33.780
but we address them late.

00:48:33.780 --> 00:48:36.280
And so therefore,
terrible problems

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:37.779
develop before we get there.

00:48:37.779 --> 00:48:39.570
But I'll tell you what
I would like to see,

00:48:39.570 --> 00:48:40.778
I don't know that I will see.

00:48:40.778 --> 00:48:42.860
First of all, I'd like
to just see immediately,

00:48:42.860 --> 00:48:44.390
lots more technology at work.

00:48:44.390 --> 00:48:46.840
I'd like to see a different
tax policy so that we

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:49.390
have incentives for
farmers so that they

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:50.355
will adopt technology.

00:48:50.355 --> 00:48:51.450
I mean, think about this.

00:48:51.450 --> 00:48:54.340
If water is a free
input, why would you

00:48:54.340 --> 00:48:58.110
spend one penny for
technology to save water?

00:48:58.110 --> 00:48:59.402
It makes no sense.

00:48:59.402 --> 00:49:01.360
And I have a story that
is an East Coast story,

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:06.880
but people always can't quite
believe it, but it's true.

00:49:06.880 --> 00:49:11.052
In 1980, in-- well
let me step back.

00:49:11.052 --> 00:49:12.760
New York City gets
its water from a bunch

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:14.760
of-- from the greater watershed.

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:16.090
It's very healthy, good water.

00:49:16.090 --> 00:49:18.930
And it comes from these enormous
water pipes that are probably

00:49:18.930 --> 00:49:21.531
about the size, or maybe half
the size of this large room

00:49:21.531 --> 00:49:22.530
that we're in right now.

00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:24.970
You could drive a truck
through it, it's so large.

00:49:24.970 --> 00:49:27.340
And these are
massive water pipes.

00:49:27.340 --> 00:49:30.030
There are two of them
that feed New York.

00:49:30.030 --> 00:49:32.930
And in 1980, they discovered
in one of the pipes

00:49:32.930 --> 00:49:36.175
that there was a leak, a
leak in one of the pipes.

00:49:36.175 --> 00:49:38.030
And it wasn't just any leak.

00:49:38.030 --> 00:49:41.070
It was an unusually large leak.

00:49:41.070 --> 00:49:46.360
The leak was leaking 35 million
gallons every single day.

00:49:46.360 --> 00:49:48.320
It's a lot of water.

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:50.990
So if you were leaking
35 million gallons a day,

00:49:50.990 --> 00:49:53.410
and there was a cost to
that water of $1 a gallon

00:49:53.410 --> 00:49:56.757
or a penny a gallon or
tenth of a penny a gallon,

00:49:56.757 --> 00:49:58.590
what you would probably
do is you'd probably

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:01.720
pretty quickly do a
cost-benefit analysis and say,

00:50:01.720 --> 00:50:04.320
got to fix the damn leak.

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:07.230
But instead, the
decision was made,

00:50:07.230 --> 00:50:08.355
they knew it was a problem.

00:50:08.355 --> 00:50:10.610
They knew sooner or later
they'd have to fix it.

00:50:10.610 --> 00:50:13.950
But the attitude was
infrastructure is expensive,

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:15.930
and water is free.

00:50:15.930 --> 00:50:19.860
So if water is free, why fix it?

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:23.410
And so now we are
1980, 2000, 2010-- so

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:25.930
now we are 34
years later, is it?

00:50:25.930 --> 00:50:30.830
We're 34, 35 years later-- 35,
2015-- we're 35 years later.

00:50:30.830 --> 00:50:32.663
And here I'm going to
tell you where we are.

00:50:32.663 --> 00:50:37.530
35 million gallons a day,
that's a lot of water.

00:50:37.530 --> 00:50:40.652
Last year, they made
the decision to fix it.

00:50:40.652 --> 00:50:42.360
They have a seven-year
project to fix it.

00:50:42.360 --> 00:50:44.151
It's going to cost
about a billion dollars.

00:50:44.151 --> 00:50:47.450
So 41 years after they
discovered a leak,

00:50:47.450 --> 00:50:52.220
leaking 35 million gallons
a day, it will be fixed.

00:50:52.220 --> 00:50:54.930
Now, that is a big story.

00:50:54.930 --> 00:50:57.970
Bring that down to
microcosm to a farmer.

00:50:57.970 --> 00:51:02.324
As long as water is free, or
functionally free, or highly

00:51:02.324 --> 00:51:03.740
subsidized, as
long as it's highly

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:06.010
subsidized for
homeowners, we're going

00:51:06.010 --> 00:51:07.762
to keep doing silly,
reckless things.

00:51:07.762 --> 00:51:10.095
So one of things that Israel
does, I didn't get a chance

00:51:10.095 --> 00:51:11.990
to talk about
before, is it charges

00:51:11.990 --> 00:51:13.610
a real price for the water.

00:51:13.610 --> 00:51:17.590
But every penny that's
charged goes to a lockbox.

00:51:17.590 --> 00:51:20.360
It's used only for water
infrastructure and water

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:21.385
management.

00:51:21.385 --> 00:51:23.760
What happens in America is
the same mayors I talked about

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:27.490
before, they have water
fees, they have sewage fees,

00:51:27.490 --> 00:51:31.280
it goes into the general pot, it
goes into the general treasury,

00:51:31.280 --> 00:51:33.740
and they don't use
it to fix the water.

00:51:33.740 --> 00:51:36.415
And so therefore, they're happy
to be sloppy with their water.

00:51:36.415 --> 00:51:38.890
And that's something
that we can't afford.

00:51:38.890 --> 00:51:40.640
Maybe we could afford
it once upon a time,

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:43.660
I'm arguing that we cannot
afford it going forward.

00:51:43.660 --> 00:51:44.620
So when do we fix it?

00:51:44.620 --> 00:51:47.220
We fix governance, we
fix our infrastructure,

00:51:47.220 --> 00:51:50.099
we fix our financing
system, we perhaps

00:51:50.099 --> 00:51:52.640
have some eminent domain, when
we say somebody's use of water

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:54.742
is inappropriate
for the rest of us.

00:51:54.742 --> 00:51:56.950
And we have to start thinking
about this differently.

00:51:56.950 --> 00:52:00.070
And we have to have our
federal government rethink

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:02.740
the way it manages water.

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:04.800
Because the management
of water is back

00:52:04.800 --> 00:52:08.340
in a time when there were
different society completely,

00:52:08.340 --> 00:52:10.610
not scarcity issues
looming, and not

00:52:10.610 --> 00:52:12.527
the problems that we have today.

00:52:12.527 --> 00:52:13.860
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank you so much.

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:16.615
So I want to ask about one thing
you didn't mention much about

00:52:16.615 --> 00:52:18.239
was the terms stormwater
and greywater.

00:52:18.239 --> 00:52:20.720
And I was wondering, do you
think it's practical for us

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:23.180
to actually separate
out-- I mean,

00:52:23.180 --> 00:52:25.860
like, there are many types
of sewage, in a sense,

00:52:25.860 --> 00:52:28.550
and in a lot of places,
stormwater and sewage

00:52:28.550 --> 00:52:30.930
is all just the same, and all
goes to the same treatment

00:52:30.930 --> 00:52:34.300
plant, and then you end up with
sewage overflowing when there's

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:35.970
too much rain, and so forth.

00:52:35.970 --> 00:52:37.970
Is it practical to
actually develop

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:40.470
sort of separate systems for
stormwater, for greywater,

00:52:40.470 --> 00:52:41.510
for black water?

00:52:41.510 --> 00:52:43.740
I mean, greywater and
stormwater are easier to treat

00:52:43.740 --> 00:52:45.849
and more reusable.

00:52:45.849 --> 00:52:47.390
Do you think that's
a practical thing

00:52:47.390 --> 00:52:50.510
to do in the United States?

00:52:50.510 --> 00:52:53.320
SETH SIEGEL: The answer is
yes, I think it's doable.

00:52:53.320 --> 00:52:55.864
I think it's a question
of prioritization.

00:52:55.864 --> 00:52:58.030
And you have to make a
decision as to where you want

00:52:58.030 --> 00:52:59.880
to spend your water dollars.

00:52:59.880 --> 00:53:03.820
I think that probably, there
are possibly better dollars

00:53:03.820 --> 00:53:05.347
to be spent first.

00:53:05.347 --> 00:53:07.430
But I think this is one
of these moments where you

00:53:07.430 --> 00:53:09.300
have to consider all options.

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:11.410
And regionally
speaking, in some places

00:53:11.410 --> 00:53:14.070
where you have lots of rain
that gets lost to the sea,

00:53:14.070 --> 00:53:16.110
is a good place to be
thinking about this.

00:53:16.110 --> 00:53:20.251
I think storm capture
water is a fabulous idea.

00:53:20.251 --> 00:53:22.500
I agree with you that it's--
it's not as easy to treat

00:53:22.500 --> 00:53:23.708
as you may think, by the way.

00:53:23.708 --> 00:53:26.217
Stormwater raindrops, when
they fall from the sky,

00:53:26.217 --> 00:53:27.050
they're pretty pure.

00:53:27.050 --> 00:53:29.200
But the second
they hit the soil,

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:31.990
they pick up what's left from
the car, and truck, and bus

00:53:31.990 --> 00:53:35.990
exhaust, and they pick up lots
of silt, and lots of sand.

00:53:35.990 --> 00:53:38.950
And so by the time they get
into the treatment center,

00:53:38.950 --> 00:53:40.110
it's pretty dirty.

00:53:40.110 --> 00:53:43.720
It's filled with chemicals,
and it's pretty dirty stuff.

00:53:43.720 --> 00:53:46.721
But it's a good idea to have
that as part of the mix,

00:53:46.721 --> 00:53:48.220
particularly in
parts of the country

00:53:48.220 --> 00:53:51.590
where you have a significant
amount of seasonal rain.

00:53:51.590 --> 00:53:53.590
So you can trap that rain.

00:53:53.590 --> 00:53:54.610
You can treat that rain.

00:53:54.610 --> 00:53:57.617
And then you can put
it in large reservoirs

00:53:57.617 --> 00:53:58.825
where it can be useful later.

00:53:58.825 --> 00:54:01.074
And by the way, Israel does
something just like that,

00:54:01.074 --> 00:54:02.740
but they haven't been
doing that as much

00:54:02.740 --> 00:54:06.110
lately, because they made the
decision that it's actually

00:54:06.110 --> 00:54:09.860
more cost effective
to take water

00:54:09.860 --> 00:54:12.340
from sewage, because
there's a lot of it,

00:54:12.340 --> 00:54:13.680
and treat that and reuse that.

00:54:13.680 --> 00:54:16.410
But they have, as
you saw in my chart,

00:54:16.410 --> 00:54:17.950
they have a little
bit of stormwater

00:54:17.950 --> 00:54:19.200
recapture that they use now.

00:54:19.200 --> 00:54:21.616
But I think it may make more
sense for parts of the United

00:54:21.616 --> 00:54:24.700
States that have seasonally
high amounts of water, though.

